Merkel's Stage
LONDON — — Facing Theresa May, Britain's new prime minister, is a daunting task: implementing the wishes of British voters — or more precisely, those of England and Wales — to "leave the EU," and managing the profound consequences that will entail.
The challenge she confronts dwarfs those of her recent predecessors.
But she may have the ability to get the job done.
No one should underestimating Merkel.
Like German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who has demonstrated courage in a series of crises, everything needed to accomplish the task is in May's hands.
She is smart and tenacious, and has no patience for empty rhetoric.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology and excels at exercising control, operating within self-defined boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues at hand.
May has won most of the battles she has been involved in and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded means against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination – she needs to use it fully to lead the Brexit process.
Brexit is already under way and there can be no doubt about that.
Even though Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be undone.
She has said repeatedly that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers agree with her.
But Mei has not yet given a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is extremely difficult to accomplish.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
You would find it hard to know exactly what you will be eating.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, your feelings about various possible pairings might be quite different.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people might primarily focus on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others may be more concerned with gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality that the Leave camp often overlooks is that the EU will not hand over benefits to Britain for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win hearts or punish Britain for not wanting to join (such inflammatory rhetoric is sometimes rampant, as when Britain's new Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson spoke of "Hitlerian imperialism").
Instead, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has their own political or commercial interests to protect.
For May, the core challenge over the coming months will be to determine what Britain's aims should be in the hard negotiations on its relationship with the EU (and, in trade matters, with the world) once they start.
Given the scope of the agenda (there are at least six major themes that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are finished, my granddaughter who is 11 now might already be in college!
) We must prioritize to prevent the negotiations from dragging on for even longer.
The goal is naturally to find a balance between allowing British exports of goods and services (especially financial services) into other European countries and restricting EU citizens' access to the UK.
Negotiators will have to make greater concessions in one area the more they gain in another.
Mi must fully leverage her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the rationality of the negotiation deal.
But even if she can achieve her goals successfully, she will still find that dissatisfaction extends not just to one part — as is inevitable — but to all.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing the government of Xi: narrowing the growing gap in British society that Brexit has exposed.
The white-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, long estranged from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the supposed agents of globalization — the EU.
The big cities of England — especially London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have received no benefits.
&lt;span&gt;Due to a lack of confidence in the leftist leader Jeremy Corbyn's Labour Party, many blue-collar workers eventually fell prey to the populist promises of Leave.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span&gt;"We will reverse globalization," they said.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span&gt;"We will get rid of immigrants who depress wages and redirect millions of pounds that go to the EU into public services."&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span&gt;They promised that Brexit would allow Britain to recapture a safer, more prosperous past.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span&gt;Leavers cannot truly deliver on these promises.&lt;/span&gt;
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can it cut off migration from the EU.
Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
即使 economic downturn leads to a decrease in immigration, workers who voted for Brexit may still feel disheartened, finding low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public services under intense pressure.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already unleashed an uncontrollable populist mood swing.
Just as Donald Trump's efforts have failed to improve the circumstances for American working-class voters, despite how things may appear, Brexit offers no benefits to those who chose it.
Though it has many advantages, such a challenge may still prove too much for May to overcome.
